      <span class="blg-date">Thu, November 14th, 2019</span>
      <h2 class="index-header">And so it begins.</h2>
      <p>So this moring, cup of coffee in hand, I sat down and began thinking about the user stories for a bug tracking system.  Now, I've never worked in a professional enviornment, and so while I had a pretty good idea what features were inportant in a bug tracker, I didn't want to just start coding away only to have to stop and backtrack because I had overlooked some important feature/dependency. So I decided that a better way of spending the next hour was to do some research.. and research I did!</p>
        <p>I stubled on a few resources, I found this <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_rwBbhur9dw&t=62s" target="_blank">Youtube Link</a> that described what bug tracking / issue tracking software does, but at an elementary level. It was a five minute watch, and aside from the generated voice it wasn't half bad.</p>
        <p>Afterwards, I did some more googling and stubled upon a pretty interesting design source from Oracle: <a href="https://docs.oracle.com/cd/E14373_01/appdev.32/e13363/issue_track_obj.htm#HTMAD010" target="_blank">How to design an Issue Tracking Application</a>. This page is part of the "Application Express Advanced Tutorials" series hosted by Oracle and I thought that it was a really good starting point for collecting the application specs.</p>
        <p>Of particular interest to me was the data models (here's a link => <a href="https://docs.oracle.com/cd/E14373_01/appdev.32/e13363/img/ui_data_model.gif" target="_blank">IMAGE</a>). I'll be using these three models as the data store for my issue tracking app (thanks Oracle).</p>
        <p>Last night I added the <a href="https://github.com/plataformatec/devise" target="_blank">Devise</a> Gem to my portfolio for authentication, generated the views and began customizing them, figured I could do this all day and still not be happy, so I then stopped, pushed to Github, merged the branch, updated local, pushed to Heroku, migrated the database, created a user for myself and then disabled registration... because who'd really want an account on this site... it isn't as if I offer anything worth anything yet :)</p>
        <p> on a related note, I started using MS Visual Code today. Really nice editor, builtin terminal, which is nice. I'll have to figure out how to make Power line look a bit better. But It is a bit faster than Atom, which in my limited experience is a nice editor. I tip my hat to Kjartan Manvelyan for the recommendation.</p>
        <p>Okay, just writing now because I doubt I'll have a chance later. Have a great day.</p>
    </div>

